  "response": "During World War II, some French citizens and military personnel collaborated with Nazi Germany after France's defeat in 1940. The most notable collaborationist group was the Vichy regime, led by Marshal Philippe P\u00e9tain, which governed the southern part of France while the Nazis occupied the northern region. \n\nSome specific examples of French collaboration include:\n\n1. Vichy French military units fought alongside Germans against Allied forces.\n\n2. The Vichy French Milice (paramilitary force) actively helped the Nazis hunt down resistance members and Jews.\n\n3. The Division Charlemagne was a Waffen-SS unit composed primarily of French volunteers who fought for Nazi Germany, particularly on the Eastern Front against Soviet forces.\n\nHowever, it's important to note that many French people also resisted the Nazi occupation through the French Resistance, and not all French people supported collaboration. After the war, France was considered one of the victorious Allied powers.",
